# Code Quality

## Always

- Use names that reveal intent, domain meaning, and units where relevant.
- Keep functions focused on one level of abstraction.
- Prefer simple control flow; use early returns to reduce deep nesting.
- Remove duplication when it improves clarity, not by forcing premature abstractions.
- Keep data immutable by default when mutation is not required.
- Make invalid states hard to represent through types, validation, or clear invariants.
- Add comments only to explain non-obvious decisions, tradeoffs, or constraints.
- Avoid clever code when straightforward code communicates the same behavior.